05036nam a22006495i 9780226789408DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267894087 a10.7208/97802267894082doi  a(DE-B1597)523707  a(OCoLC)1125186701  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGA205 -- A64 2012eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a526.09/0100aAncient Perspectives :bMaps and Their Place in Mesopotamia, Egypt, Greece, and Rome /ced. by Richard J. A. Talbert. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b9 color plates, 82 halftones, 34 line drawings, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Kenneth Nebenzahl Jr. Lectures in the History of Cartography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Expression of Terrestrial and Celestial Order in Ancient Mesopotamia -- t2. From Topography to Cosmos: Ancient Egypt’s Multiple Maps -- t3. Mapping the World: Greek Initiatives from Homer to Eratosthenes -- t4. Ptolemy’s Geography: Mapmaking and the Scientific Enterprise -- t5. Greek and Roman Surveying and Surveying Instruments -- t6. Urbs Roma to Orbis Romanus: Roman Mapping on the Grand Scale -- t7. Putting the World in Order: Mapping in Roman Texts -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAncient Perspectives encompasses a vast arc of space and time—Western Asia to North Africa and Europe from the third millennium BCE to the fifth century CE—to explore mapmaking and worldviews in the ancient civilizations of Mesopotamia, Egypt, Greece, and Rome. In each society, maps served as critical economic, political, and personal tools, but there was little consistency in how and why they were made. Much like today, maps in antiquity meant very different things to different people. Ancient Perspectives presents an ambitious, fresh overview of cartography and its uses. The seven chapters range from broad-based analyses of mapping in Mesopotamia and Egypt to a close focus on Ptolemy’s ideas for drawing a world map based on the theories of his Greek predecessors at Alexandria. The remarkable accuracy of Mesopotamian city-plans is revealed, as is the creation of maps by Romans to support the proud claim that their emperor’s rule was global in its reach. By probing the instruments and techniques of both Greek and Roman surveyors, one chapter seeks to uncover how their extraordinary planning of roads, aqueducts, and tunnels was achieved. Even though none of these civilizations devised the means to measure time or distance with precision, they still conceptualized their surroundings, natural and man-made, near and far, and felt the urge to record them by inventive means that this absorbing volume reinterprets and compares.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCartographyzEgyptxHistory. 0aCartographyzGreecexHistory. 0aCartographyzIraqxHistory. 0aCartographyzRomexHistory. 0aGeography, Ancient. 0aSurveyingxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aIrby, Georgia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Connor, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRochberg, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalway, Benet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalbert, Richard J. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalbert, Richard J. A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabu